The expression `Pr[=x | $[0..n]]` represents the probability of selecting the element `x` when choosing uniformly at random from the list `[0, 1, ..., n]`. 

Since `x` and `y` are elements of `ZMod (n + 1)`, they are integers modulo `n + 1`. The list `[0, 1, ..., n]` contains exactly `n + 1` elements, which is the size of the type `ZMod (n + 1)`. 

When we select uniformly at random from this list, each element has an equal probability of being chosen. The probability of selecting any specific element (like `x` or `y`) is therefore `1 / (n + 1)`. 

Since `x` and `y` are arbitrary elements of `ZMod (n + 1)`, and the selection process is uniform, the probability of selecting `x` should be the same as the probability of selecting `y`. 

