`⊢ Pr[=x | $[0..n]] = Pr[=y | $[0..n]]`

Let's think about what `Pr[=x | $[0..n]]` means. The notation $[0..n]$ represents a computation that generates a value in `Fin (n + 1)`, which corresponds to `ZMod (n + 1)`. The computation $[0..n]$ is essentially selecting a value uniformly at random from the range `[0, n]`.

In the context of `ZMod (n + 1)`, the values `0` to `n` are distinct elements of the finite field `ZMod (n + 1)`. When we compute $[0..n]$, we're generating a value that's uniformly distributed over these `n + 1` elements.

So, `Pr[=x | $[0..n]]` is the probability that the computation $[0..n]$ results in the value `x`. Since the computation is generating a value uniformly at random from `0` to `n`, each of the `n + 1` possible values has an equal probability of being chosen. Therefore, the probability of getting any specific value `x` is `1 / (n + 1)`.

Similarly, `Pr[=y | $[0..n]]` is the probability of getting `y`, which is also `1 / (n + 1)`.

Therefore, `Pr[=x | $[0..n]] = Pr[=y | $[0..n]]`.

